<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41040d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41040d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41040d"> 40(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">C</font> conspirator</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The offence of &ldquo;<mark>Conspiracy</mark>&ldquo; may be defined as &ldquo;an agreement or combination between <mark>two or more persons</mark> to do an unlawful act.&ldquo; The essence of the offence lies in the agreement. One person cannot alone be guilty of conspiracy and for this reason a husband and wife who have entered into a criminal agreement to which they are the only parties, cannot be charged with conspiracy under English Law, which still regards them, for this purpose, as one person. <small> Maud I. Crofts, <a name="MICW" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MICW"><cite title="source">Women under English Law</cite></a>, 1st ed. (1925) 46</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
